<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06038h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06038h">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06038h"> 38(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pictures in clouds / fire,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;est ce que montre ce passe-temps bien connu qui consiste &agrave; d&eacute;couvrir des formes famili&egrave;res, telles que celles de la t&ecirc;te humaine ou de certains animaux, dans des rochers &eacute;loign&eacute;s et dans les nuages, ou encore &agrave; apercevoir <mark>des images dans le feu</mark>, et ainsi de suite. Les formes vagues et ind&eacute;cises des masses de rochers, <mark>de nuages</mark> ou de charbons ardents offrent un large champ &agrave; la fantaisie cr&eacute;atrice; <font color="green">[This is what this well-known hobby of discovering familiar shapes, such as those of the human head or of certain animals, in distant rocks and clouds, or seeing images in the fire shows. And so on. The vague and undecided forms of masses of rocks, clouds, or burning coals offer a wide field to creative fantasy;]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
